<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920109-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>920109-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- DSC Communications Corp.:   Firm Receives Commitment   To Buy $41 Million of Gear</HL><DATE>01/09/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   BEL DIGI PAC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)REGIONAL TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (RTL)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   DSC Communications Corp. said it received a commitmentcalling for it to sell to Pacific Bell signal transfer pointand related switching equipment valued at $41 million.   The agreement marks Pacific Bell's first order of suchequipment since a rash of local telephone outages last summerwere traced to a error that DSC made in STP-related software.The problem caused outages in areas served by Pacific Bell, aunit of Pacific Telesis Group, and Bell Atlantic Corp.</LP><TEXT>   Signal transfer points speed the routing of calls througha telephone network and allow telephone companies to offerservices such as caller identification.   Sales by DSC, based in Plano, Texas, dropped 23% in thethird quarter from a year earlier and it posted a $78.8million loss for the period. Sales of its signal transferpoint and related equipment last year dropped to less thanhalf the $62 million in sales, or 12% of the company'srevenue, that the product line recorded in 1990. However, aspokesman said, &quot;we're looking for a very good year in STPbusiness&quot; in 1992.   DSC said a small portion of the equipment was deliveredlast year and most of the deliveries will be made this year.</TEXT></DOC>